-- South African Stocks Fall For Third Day, Led Down by ARB, Italtile, Sappi
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2011-02-09T16:28:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-09/south-african-equities-arb-holdings-gold-reef-italtile-sappi.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index dropped for a third day, declining 111.30, or 0.3
percent, to 32,677.56 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    ARB Holdings Ltd . (ARH SJ), a retailer of power cables and
conductors, fell 30 cents, or 7.9 percent, to 3.50 rand, the
biggest drop since September. The company reported net income in
the six months through December declined to 35.4 million rand
($4.9 million) from 35.7 million rand.    Gold Reef Resorts Ltd . (GDF SJ), a gaming and casino
company, snapped two days of losses, jumping 1.05 rand, or 6.3
percent, to 17.70 rand. The company was today presenting legal
arguments in favor of its merger with Tsogo Sun Holdings at the
Competition Tribunal.    Italtile Ltd . (ITE SJ), a ceramic-tile retailer, dropped
the most in seven weeks, losing 10 cents, or 2.4 percent, to
4.10 rand. Gianpaolo Ravazzotti, the company’s chief executive
officer, was killed in a plane accident near Plettenberg Bay on
the nation’s south coast last night, the company said in a
statement. Succession plans will be announced in “due course.”    Naspers Ltd . (NPN SJ), Africa’s biggest media company,
declined for a third day, losing 1.01 rand, or 0.3 percent, to
394.99 rand.  Tencent Holdings Ltd ., which is 35 percent owned by
Naspers and China’s largest Internet company by market value,
declined 1.6 percent, falling for a third day in Hong Kong
trading.    Sappi Ltd . (SAP SJ), the world’s largest maker of glossy
paper, fell the most since Nov. 30, dropping 1.52 rand, or 4
percent, to 36.99 rand. The company said it would buy back as
much as $150 million of the principal amount on its $500
million, 6.75 percent guaranteed notes due 2012. Sappi also said
it has returned to profit, reporting earnings of 7 U.S. cents
per share in the first quarter of financial 2011, compared to a
loss of 10 cents a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
